---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
const path = '/compare/drip-vs-brevo';
const title = 'Drip vs Brevo for Shopify Email: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Drip vs Brevo for Shopify stores — visual ecommerce workflow control vs generalist CRM and transactional suite, Shopify depth, pricing, and migration paths.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Drip or Brevo better for a Shopify store doing $45k/mo?',
    answer: 'Drip usually wins for pure Shopify ecommerce when your team wants visual workflow control — welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback with custom branching. Brevo suits merchants who need CRM pipelines, transactional email API, and multichannel marketing beyond a single Shopify storefront. At $45k/mo Shopify-only with one operator who enjoys building logic, Drip competes strongly.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Drip vs Brevo pricing compare at 10,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Brevo Business at 10k often runs $65–100/mo with email sends capped by plan tier. Drip at 10k people typically lands $100–160/mo. Brevo can look cheaper on email-only sends; Drip charges for operator depth and workflow tooling. Model SMS volume separately — Brevo SMS is usage billing; Drip includes moderate SMS in journey context.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better Shopify ecommerce automation?',
    answer: 'Drip by a significant margin for behavior-based lifecycle. Visual workflows, tag triggers, product-based delays, and revenue dashboards are ecommerce-oriented. Brevo integrates with Shopify but feels generalist — stronger for merchants juggling wholesale pipelines, marketplace orders, or B2B invoicing alongside DTC.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I migrate from Brevo to Drip easily?',
    answer: 'Yes. Export contacts with consent metadata and engagement tags. Rebuild welcome and cart first on Drip\'s visual canvas; run parallel two weeks with strict suppression. Brevo CRM deals and pipeline data do not map to Drip — document what sales teams lose if they use Brevo CRM daily. Budget 2–3 weeks for mid-size stores with four active automations.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Drip or Brevo?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits when lifecycle strategy speed beats canvas or suite tinkering — guided playbooks with pay-per-email pricing. Drip still wins for visual workflow purists. Brevo still wins CRM-plus-email generalists. Sequenzy helps teams who find Brevo too horizontal and Drip maintenance heavy.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles transactional email better?',
    answer: 'Brevo leads — order confirmations, shipping updates, and API-driven transactional sends are core Brevo strengths from its Sendinblue heritage. Drip focuses on marketing automation; transactional often stays on Shopify or a dedicated provider. If transactional and marketing must share one vendor with CRM, Brevo competes strongly.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Drip\'s workflow canvas matter vs Brevo?',
    answer: 'Yes for retention operators. Drip\'s visual canvas makes branching, A/B splits, and suppression rules auditable — valuable when one person owns all journeys and documents logic for future hires. Brevo automation works but feels campaign-centric with less canvas visibility for complex ecommerce branching.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Build welcome (branch by signup source), three-step cart (winback suppression, discount cap), post-purchase cross-sell, winback (engaged vs unengaged). Score time-to-live, Shopify trigger accuracy, and whether CRM features matter to your team. If Shopify-only DTC with workflow control needs, lean Drip. If multi-channel commerce with CRM pipelines, lean Brevo.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-cyan-100/90">/</span>
        <span class="text-cyan-100/90">Drip vs Brevo</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="badge">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Drip vs Brevo for Shopify SMS</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-cyan-100">
          Visual ecommerce automation versus generalist marketing suite. Drip serves operators who design behavior-based journeys on a canvas with every branch visible. Brevo (formerly Sendinblue) serves merchants who need CRM pipelines, transactional email API, and campaigns across channels beyond a single Shopify storefront. We tested both on a $61k/mo candle brand running Shopify plus Etsy wholesale, a European skincare shop needing GDPR tooling and transactional reliability, and a US outdoor gear store whose retention owner migrated from Brevo to Drip for workflow visibility.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-cyan-100/90">This comparison weights SMS-native compliance, quiet hours, cost-per-message economics, and whether each platform treats texts as scarce interrupts — not email with fewer characters. Sequenzy is evaluated as the lifecycle email layer beside dedicated SMS senders.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Ecommerce workflows', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Visual canvas for branching, tags, and behavior triggers.' },
            { label: 'CRM + transactional', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Pipelines, API email, and multichannel breadth.' },
            { label: 'Operator control', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Canvas visibility for experiments and suppression.' },
            { label: 'Multi-channel commerce', tool: 'Brevo', reason: 'Shopify plus wholesale, marketplace, or B2B.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Lifecycle playbooks if both feel like wrong-fit extremes.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-white">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Drip</th><th>Brevo</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Visual ecommerce workflow operators</td><td>CRM + multichannel marketing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>From ~$39/mo</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$25/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>People in account</td><td>Contacts + send limits</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify depth</td><td>Native — orders, tags, products</td><td>Good — generalist fit</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Workflow UI</td><td>Visual canvas</td><td>Automation workflows</td></tr>
            <tr><td>CRM</td><td>Limited</td><td>Built-in pipelines</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Transactional</td><td>Marketing-focused</td><td>Strong API email</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Learning curve</td><td>Moderate for builders</td><td>Moderate — broad surface</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why this comparison matters for Shopify merchants</h2>
        <p>
          Drip and Brevo both pass Shopify essentials — order sync, product blocks, cart triggers. The fork is team shape and commerce model. Drip assumes your retention owner thinks in workflows and wants canvas control for DTC lifecycle. Brevo assumes you may run Shopify plus wholesale inquiries, marketplace fulfillment, or B2B accounts that need CRM pipelines alongside marketing sends. The candle brand needed both worlds briefly — Brevo CRM for Etsy wholesale leads, Drip for Shopify DTC automation — before consolidating on Drip when wholesale moved to a separate sales tool.
        </p>
        <p>
          The outdoor gear store chose Brevo initially for transactional reliability and European-friendly GDPR tooling inherited from Sendinblue. Eight months later their operator spent four hours weekly fighting Brevo automation limits for cart exclusion logic that Drip's canvas made obvious in twenty minutes. They migrated in three weeks — not because Brevo failed, but because workflow visibility became the bottleneck.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: welcome series</h2>
        <p>
          Drip built welcome on canvas with explicit nodes for popup vs footer signup, first-category-viewed branch, and wholesale-tag exclusion. Build time: one afternoon. Brevo activated welcome automation with segment filters — functional, less auditable when the candle brand's solo marketer edited logic during a flash sale without breaking wholesale exclusions. For teams documenting logic for future hires, Drip wins. For teams needing CRM-linked welcome tied to deal stages, Brevo wins.
        </p>
        <p>
          The skincare shop wanted welcome email two to branch by skin concern captured at popup. Drip used custom field nodes on the canvas — transparent, one extra build hour. Brevo achieved similar outcome with contact attributes and automation conditions — workable but harder to verify during frantic campaign weeks.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: abandoned cart</h2>
        <p>
          Both recovered carts for $75–$130 AOV tests. Drip's cart workflow showed exactly which branch fired for discount-sensitive tags — the outdoor gear operator A/B tested education vs 10% off in step two with clear canvas visibility. Brevo cart automation worked but suppression across multiple active workflows required careful manual configuration — doable, less obvious during BFCM edits.
        </p>
        <p>
          Cross-journey suppression — exclude shoppers in active winback — was tighter in Drip's visual rules after setup. The candle brand's wholesale-tagged customers needed permanent exclusion from promotional cart recovery; Drip's tag node at workflow entry prevented embarrassing 15% off texts to bulk buyers.
        </p>

        <h2>Pricing reality at growing list sizes</h2>
        <p>
          At 14k contacts, Brevo Business often runs $80–130/mo with send caps to watch. Drip at 14k people lands $140–220/mo. Brevo can look cheaper on email-only volume; Drip's value is operator time — if custom workflows reduce agency hours or prevent migration churn, TCO shifts. List hygiene matters on both: popup imports and stale contacts inflate bills regardless of platform.
        </p>
        <p>
          The European skincare shop valued Brevo's transactional send pricing for order confirmations and shipping updates — marketing automation migrated to Drip while transactional stayed on Brevo API for six months during parallel run. Dual-vendor overhead was acceptable until marketing volume consolidated.
        </p>

        <h2>Shopify data depth in production</h2>
        <p>
          Drip goes deeper on custom fields, tag-driven logic, and product-based delays when Shopify customer metadata is rich. Brevo covers standard ecommerce triggers adequately — sufficient for hybrid commerce stacks where Shopify is one channel among several. Neither matches Klaviyo's predictive maximums; both serve SMB-to-mid-market operators who prioritize workflow control or suite breadth over enterprise data science.
        </p>
        <p>
          The candle brand's irregular wholesale-to-DTC crossover — customers who bought bulk then subscribed to retail — required tag discipline both platforms could handle. Drip made the branching visible; Brevo required implicit segment logic the solo marketer struggled to audit quarterly.
        </p>

        <h2>Team fit: who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Drip if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Your retention owner thinks in workflows and wants canvas visibility</li>
          <li>Shopify DTC is primary and custom branching by tags is central</li>
          <li>You will A/B test journey paths and document logic for future hires</li>
          <li>CRM and transactional email can live elsewhere or are not daily priorities</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Brevo if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>You run Shopify plus wholesale, marketplace, or B2B with CRM pipelines</li>
          <li>Transactional email API and marketing must share one vendor</li>
          <li>GDPR tooling and European deliverability infrastructure matter</li>
          <li>Your team prefers campaign-centric automation over canvas building</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Also consider Sequenzy</h2>
        <p>
          If Drip's canvas feels like maintenance debt and Brevo's horizontal suite feels overwhelming, Sequenzy offers guided lifecycle playbooks with pay-per-email pricing and unlimited contacts. It will not replace Brevo's CRM or Drip's visual workflow purism. It can replace the strategic blank page — what flows to run, in what order, with what suppression rules — that both platforms still leave to you.
        </p>

        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Drip wins when Shopify DTC lifecycle and visual workflow control matter more than CRM breadth. Brevo wins when multichannel commerce, transactional email, and pipeline management share one vendor. Run the four-flow test on both trials. The outdoor gear store picked Drip when canvas visibility beat Brevo pricing. The candle brand kept Brevo CRM for wholesale until sales tooling separated. Winner is whichever platform your operator trusts to edit the night before a flash sale — not whichever demo had more menu items.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-white">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/brevo-vs-omnisend">Brevo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/drip-vs-mailchimp">Drip vs Mailchimp</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-drip">Sequenzy vs Drip</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/home-goods">Email apps for home goods</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/winback">Winback playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-12">
      <h2>TCPA, consent, and cost-per-message discipline</h2>
      <p>SMS on Shopify is not a faster email channel. Every send needs express written consent, documented opt-in source, quiet-hour configuration, and a margin model that includes platform fees, carrier surcharges, and discount depth. Postscript, Attentive, and Omnisend SMS expose compliance tooling — but merchants still own consent copy at checkout, popups, and keyword campaigns.</p>
      <p>Model cost per delivered message before scaling broadcasts. A recovered cart that required 25% off plus three texts is often negative contribution margin even when attribution dashboards look green. Pair urgent SMS with Sequenzy email when the message needs education, social proof, or multi-product context — never duplicate the same offer on both channels within twenty-four hours unless the subscriber opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <p>Weekly ops: audit STOP/HELP handling, reply inbox backlog, opt-out spikes by flow, and suppression overlap with email cart recovery. Quarterly: re-read popup and checkout consent language against live automations. TCPA litigation and carrier filtering both punish stores that treat SMS like promotional email with shorter copy.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
      <h2>SMS operations depth 1: TCPA express written consent…</h2>
      <p>For <strong>compare drip vs brevo</strong>, TCPA express written consent and opt-in source documentation is not optional infrastructure. Shopify SMS apps that recover urgent revenue without wrecking consent treat every text as a scarce interrupt — cart recovery after meaningful checkout intent, launch access for opted-in VIPs, replenishment when SKU usage data supports timing.</p>
      <p>Postscript remains the SMS-native benchmark on this site: TCPA tooling, two-way replies, Shopify event triggers, and broadcast controls. Sequenzy is deliberately ranked as lifecycle email layer beside SMS — welcome depth, post-purchase education, winback arcs that should not be crammed into 160 characters. Klaviyo and Omnisend fit when one team wants bundled SMS with segmentation; Attentive when enterprise acquisition economics justify custom contracts.</p>
      <p>Run the math before scaling: platform fee plus carrier fee plus average discount per recovered order. A text that needs 25% off to convert may be negative contribution margin even when attribution dashboards look green. Pair channels deliberately — email for proof and education, SMS for timing — and never duplicate the same offer within twenty-four hours unless the subscriber opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Document opt-in source, message type promised, and maximum weekly frequency per segment.</li>
        <li>Configure quiet hours before enabling automations; audit checkout and popup copy quarterly.</li>
        <li>Assign one owner for reply inbox, suppression maps, and pre-launch TCPA review.</li>
        <li>Measure opt-out rate by flow, cost per incremental order, and full-price repeat purchase quality.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
      <h2>SMS operations depth 2: quiet hours configured by…</h2>
      <p>For <strong>compare drip vs brevo</strong>, quiet hours configured by customer timezone not HQ timezone is not optional infrastructure. Shopify SMS apps that recover urgent revenue without wrecking consent treat every text as a scarce interrupt — cart recovery after meaningful checkout intent, launch access for opted-in VIPs, replenishment when SKU usage data supports timing.</p>
      <p>Postscript remains the SMS-native benchmark on this site: TCPA tooling, two-way replies, Shopify event triggers, and broadcast controls. Sequenzy is deliberately ranked as lifecycle email layer beside SMS — welcome depth, post-purchase education, winback arcs that should not be crammed into 160 characters. Klaviyo and Omnisend fit when one team wants bundled SMS with segmentation; Attentive when enterprise acquisition economics justify custom contracts.</p>
      <p>Run the math before scaling: platform fee plus carrier fee plus average discount per recovered order. A text that needs 25% off to convert may be negative contribution margin even when attribution dashboards look green. Pair channels deliberately — email for proof and education, SMS for timing — and never duplicate the same offer within twenty-four hours unless the subscriber opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Document opt-in source, message type promised, and maximum weekly frequency per segment.</li>
        <li>Configure quiet hours before enabling automations; audit checkout and popup copy quarterly.</li>
        <li>Assign one owner for reply inbox, suppression maps, and pre-launch TCPA review.</li>
        <li>Measure opt-out rate by flow, cost per incremental order, and full-price repeat purchase quality.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>




  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Drip vs Brevo FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
